cluster_relations.rel_desc: Socialist movements are depicted as seeking to overthrow oppressive regimes.
remarks: Subject chosen as socialist movements, though uprisings share the same target.

cluster_relations.rel_desc: Uprisings around the world also sought to overthrow oppressive regimes.
remarks: Relation mirrors that for socialist movements; text uses joint subject.

args.canonical_rel_desc: Actor (e.g., movement or uprising) aims to overthrow or remove the target regime or power structure.
args.justification: Both relations describe collective political actors (socialist movements, uprisings) whose explicit aim is to overthrow oppressive regimes; they share identical adversarial, regime-change intent toward the same type of object, so one canonical predicate capturing the goal of overthrow is appropriate.
args.remark: Use qualifiers (temporal, spatial) to distinguish specific episodes; the canonical predicate focuses on the general regime-overthrow intent.

args.justification: These relations encode which regimes are targeted for overthrow by contentious political actors, fitting a regime-change targeting family of relations rather than a generic adversarial or compositional link.

The semantic core is an intentional action/goal (seeking to overthrow) directed by an agent toward a target, which is best modeled as an agency/intentional-action relation rather than mere association.
